# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spice-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] An analogue signal uses some attribute of the medium to convey the signal's information.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] For example, an aneroid barometer uses the angular position of a needle on top of a contracting and expanding box as the signal to convey the information of changes in atmospheric pressure.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Electrical signals may represent information by changing their voltage, current, frequency, or total charge.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Information is converted from some other physical form (such as sound, light, temperature, pressure, position) to an electrical signal by a transducer which converts one type of energy into another (e.g. a microphone).
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The signals take any value from a given range, and each unique signal value represents different information.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Any change in the signal is meaningful, and each level of the signal represents a different level of the phenomenon that it represents.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] For example, suppose the signal is being used to represent temperature, with one volt representing one degree Celsius.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In such a system, 10 volts would represent 10 degrees, and 10.1 volts would represent 10.1 degrees.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Another method of conveying an analogue signal is to use modulation.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In this, some base carrier signal has one of its properties altered: amplitude modulation (AM) involves altering the amplitude of a sinusoidal voltage waveform by the source information, frequency modulation (FM) changes the frequency.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Other techniques, such as phase modulation or changing the phase of the carrier signal, are also used.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In an analogue sound recording, the variation in pressure of a sound striking a microphone creates a corresponding variation in the current passing through it or voltage across it.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] An increase in the volume of the sound causes the fluctuation of the current or voltage to increase proportionally while keeping the same waveform or shape.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Mechanical, pneumatic, hydraulic, and other systems may also use analogue signals.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Analogue systems invariably include noise, random disturbances or variations, some caused by the random thermal vibrations of atomic particles.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Since all variations of an analogue signal are significant, any disturbance is equivalent to a change in the original signal and so appears as noise.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] As the signal is copied and re-copied, or transmitted over long distances, these random variations become more significant and lead to signal degradation.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Other sources of noise may include crosstalk from other signals or poorly designed components.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] These disturbances may be reduced by use of shielding and low-noise amplifiers.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Since the information is encoded differently in analogue and digital electronics, the way they process a signal is consequently different.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] All operations that can be performed on an analogue signal such as amplification, filtering, limiting, and others, can also be duplicated in the digital domain.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Every digital circuit is also an analogue circuit, in that the behaviour of any digital circuit can be explained using the rules of analogue circuits.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The use of microelectronics has made digital devices cheap and widely available.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The effect of noise on an analogue circuit is a function of the level of noise.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The greater the noise level, the more the analogue signal is disturbed, slowly becoming less usable.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Because of this, analogue signals are said to "fail gracefully".
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Analogue signals can still contain intelligible information with very high levels of noise.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Digital circuits, on the other hand, are not affected at all by the presence of noise until a certain threshold is reached, at which point they fail catastrophically.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] For digital telecommunications, it is possible to increase the noise threshold with the use of error detection and correction coding schemes and algorithms.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Nevertheless, there is still a point at which catastrophic failure of the link occurs.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics, because the information is quantized, as long as the signal stays inside a range of values, it represents the same information.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In digital circuits the signal is regenerated at each logic gate, lessening or removing noise.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In analogue circuits, signal loss can be regenerated with amplifiers.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] However, noise is cumulative throughout the system and the amplifier itself will add to the noise according to its noise figure.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] A number of factors affect how precise a signal is, mainly the noise present in the original signal and the noise added by processing (see signal-to-noise ratio).
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Fundamental physical limits such as the shot noise in components limits the resolution of analogue signals.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics additional precision is obtained by using additional digits to represent the signal.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The practical limit in the number of digits is determined by the performance of the analogue-to-digital converter (ADC), since digital operations can usually be performed without loss of precision.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The ADC takes an analogue signal and changes it into a series of binary numbers.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] The ADC may be used in simple digital display devices, e. g., thermometers or light meters but it may also be used in digital sound recording and in data acquisition.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] However, a digital-to-analogue converter (DAC) is used to change a digital signal to an analogue signal.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] A DAC takes a series of binary numbers and converts it to an analogue signal.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] It is common to find a DAC in the gain-control system of an op-amp which in turn may be used to control digital amplifiers and filters.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits are typically harder to design, requiring more skill than comparable digital systems to conceptualize.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] An analogue circuit is usually designed by hand because the application is built into the hardware.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Digital hardware, on the other hand, has a great deal of commonality across applications and can be mass-produced in a standardised form.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Hardware design consists largely of repeated identical blocks and the design process can be highly automated.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] This is one of the main reasons that digital systems have become more common than analogue devices.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] However, the application of digital hardware is a function of the software/firmware and creating this is still largely a labour-intensive process.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Since the early 2000s, there were some platforms that were developed which enabled analogue design to be defined using software - which allows faster prototyping.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Furthermore, if a digital electronic device is to interact with the real world, it will always need an analogue interface.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] For example, every digital radio receiver has an analogue preamplifier as the first stage in the receive chain.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Design of analogue circuits has been greatly eased by the advent of software circuit simulators such as SPICE.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] IBM developed their own in-house simulator, ASTAP, in the 1970s which used an unusual (compared to other simulators) sparse matrix method of circuit analysis.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits can be entirely passive, consisting of resistors, capacitors and inductors.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Active circuits also contain active elements such as transistors.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] Traditional circuits are built from lumped elements – that is, discrete components.
[src:spice-simulation/analogue-electronics] However, an alternative is distributed-element circuits, built from pieces of transmission line.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Simulating a circuit’s behavior before actually building it can greatly improve design efficiency by making faulty designs known as such, and providing insight into the behavior of electronic circuit designs.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] In particular, for integrated circuits, the tooling (photomasks) is expensive, breadboards are impractical, and probing the behavior of internal signals is extremely difficult.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Therefore, almost all IC design relies heavily on simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] The most well known analog simulator is SPICE.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Probably the best known digital simulators are those based on Verilog and VHDL.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Some electronics simulators integrate a schematic editor, a simulation engine, and an on-screen waveform display (see Figure 1), allowing designers to rapidly modify a simulated circuit and see what effect the changes have on the output.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] They also typically contain extensive model and device libraries.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] These models typically include IC specific transistor models such as BSIM, generic components such as resistors, capacitors, inductors and transformers, user defined models (such as controlled current and voltage sources, or models in Verilog-A or VHDL-AMS).
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Printed circuit board (PCB) design requires specific models as well, such as transmission lines for the traces and IBIS models for driving and receiving electronics.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] While there are strictly analog electronics circuit simulators, popular simulators often include both analog and event-driven digital simulation capabilities, and are known as mixed-mode or mixed-signal simulators if they can simulate both simultaneously.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] An entire mixed signal analysis can be driven from one integrated schematic.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] All the digital models in mixed-mode simulators provide accurate specification of propagation time and rise/fall time delays.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] The event-driven algorithm provided by mixed-mode simulators is general-purpose and supports non-digital types of data.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] For example, elements can use real or integer values to simulate DSP functions or sampled data filters.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Because the event-driven algorithm is faster than the standard SPICE matrix solution, simulation time is greatly reduced for circuits that use event-driven models in place of analog models.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Exact representations are used mainly in the analysis of transmission line and signal integrity problems where a close inspection of an IC’s I/O characteristics is needed.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Boolean logic expressions are delay-less functions that are used to provide efficient logic signal processing in an analog environment.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] These two modeling techniques use SPICE to solve a problem while the third method, digital primitives, uses mixed mode capability.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Each of these methods has its merits and target applications.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] In fact, many simulations (particularly those which use A/D technology) call for the combination of all three approaches.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Another type of simulation used mainly for power electronics represent piecewise linear algorithms.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] These algorithms use an analog (linear) simulation until a power electronic switch changes its state.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] At this time a new analog model is calculated to be used for the next simulation period.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] This methodology both enhances simulation speed and stability significantly.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Another approach that dramatically shortens the simulation time of switch-mode converters is based on average behavioral circuits that apply the switched inductor model.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] In this approach, the simulation is carried out on the average signals, voltages, and currents, and hence runs much faster.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Another advantage of this approach is that it can carry both time domain and frequency domain simulations.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] The latter can be used to extract the transfer functions in open and closed loop.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Process variations occur when the design is fabricated and circuit simulators often do not take these variations into account.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] These variations can be small, but taken together, they can change the output of a chip significantly.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] Temperature variation can also be modeled to simulate the circuit's performance through temperature ranges.
[src:spice-simulation/circuit-simulation] A common method of simulating linear circuits systems is with admittance matrices, or Y matrices.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In electronic design, a **netlist** is a description of the connectivity of an electronic circuit.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In its simplest form, a netlist consists of a list of the electronic components in a circuit and a list of the nodes they are connected to.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] A network (net) is a collection of two or more interconnected components.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] The structure, complexity and representation of netlists can vary considerably, but the fundamental purpose of every netlist is to convey connectivity information.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Netlists usually provide nothing more than instances, nodes, and perhaps some attributes of the components involved.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] If they express much more than this, they are usually considered to be a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL, or one of several languages specifically designed for input to simulators or hardware compilers (such as SPICE analog simulation netlists).
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Most netlists either contain or refer to descriptions of the parts or devices used.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Each time a part is used in a netlist, this is called an "instance".
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] These descriptions will usually list the connections that are made to that kind of device, and some basic properties of that device.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] These connection points are called "terminals" or "pins", among several other names.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] An "instance" could be anything from a MOSFET transistor or a bipolar junction transistor, to a resistor, a capacitor, or an integrated circuit chip.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In the case of a vacuum cleaner, these terminals would be the three metal prongs in the plug.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Each terminal has a name, and in continuing the vacuum cleaner example, they might be "Neutral", "Live" and "Ground".
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Usually, each instance will have a unique name, so that if you have two instances of vacuum cleaners, one might be "vac1" and the other "vac2".
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Besides their names, they might otherwise be identical.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Networks (nets) are the "wires" that connect things together in the circuit.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] There may or may not be any special attributes associated with the nets in a design, depending on the particular language the netlist is written in, and that language's features.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Instance based netlists usually provide a list of the instances used in a design.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Along with each instance, either an ordered list of net names is provided, or a list of pairs provided, of an instance port name, along with the net name to which that port is connected.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In this kind of description, the list of nets can be gathered from the connection lists, and there is no place to associate particular attributes with the nets themselves.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] SPICE is an example of instance-based netlists.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Net-based netlists usually describe all the instances and their attributes, then describe each net, and say which port they are connected on each instance.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] This allows for attributes to be associated with nets.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] EDIF is probably the most famous of the net-based netlists.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In large designs, it is a common practice to split the design into pieces, each piece becoming a "definition" which can be used as instances in the design.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In the vacuum cleaner analogy, one might have a vacuum cleaner definition with its ports, but now this definition would also include a full description of the machine's internal components and how they connect (motors, switches, etc.), like a wiring diagram does.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] A definition which includes no instances is called a "primitive" (or a "leaf", or other names); whereas a definition which includes instances is "hierarchical".
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] A "folded" hierarchy allows a single definition to be represented several times by instances.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] An "unfolded" hierarchy does not allow a definition to be used more than once in the hierarchy.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Folded hierarchies can be extremely compact.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] A small netlist of just a few instances can describe designs with a very large number of instances.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] For example, suppose definition A is a simple primitive, like a memory cell.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Then suppose definition B contains 32 instances of A; C contains 32 instances of B; D contains 32 instances of C; and E contains 32 instances of D.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] The design now contains 5 definitions (A through E) and 128 instances.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Yet, E describes a circuit that contains over a million memory cells.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In a "flat" design, only primitives are instanced.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Hierarchical designs can be recursively "exploded" ("flattened") by creating a new copy (with a new name) of each definition each time it is used.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] If the design is highly folded, expanding it like this will result in a much larger netlist database, but preserves the hierarchy dependencies.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Given a hierarchical netlist, the list of instance names in a path from the root definition to a primitive instance specifies the single unique path to that primitive.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] The paths to every primitive, taken together, comprise a large but flat netlist that is exactly equivalent to the compact hierarchical version.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Backannotation is data that could be added to a hierarchical netlist.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Usually they are kept separate from the netlist, because several such alternate sets of data could be applied to a single netlist.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] These data may have been extracted from a physical design, and might provide extra information for more accurate simulations.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Usually the data are composed of a hierarchical path and a piece of data for that primitive or finding the values of RC delay due to interconnection.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Another concept often used in netlists is that of inheritance.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Suppose a definition of a capacitor has an associated attribute called "Capacitance", corresponding to the physical property of the same name, with a default value of "100 pF" (100 picofarads).
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] Each instance of this capacitor might also have such an attribute, only with a different value of capacitance.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] And other instances might not associate any capacitance at all.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] In the case where no capacitance is specified for an instance, the instance will "inherit" the 100 pF value from its definition.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] A value specified will "override" the value on the definition.
[src:spice-simulation/netlist] If a great number of attributes end up being the same as on the definition, a great amount of information can be "inherited", and not have to be redundantly specified in the netlist, saving space, and making the design easier to read by both machines and people.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] In mathematics and science, a **nonlinear system** (or a **non-linear system**) is a system in which the change of the output is not proportional to the change of the input.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear problems are of interest to engineers, biologists, physicists, mathematicians, and many other scientists since most systems are inherently nonlinear in nature.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear dynamical systems, describing changes in variables over time, may appear chaotic, unpredictable, or counterintuitive, contrasting with much simpler linear systems.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] In other words, in a nonlinear system of equations, the equation(s) to be solved cannot be written as a linear combination of the unknown variables or functions that appear in them.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Systems can be defined as nonlinear, regardless of whether known linear functions appear in the equations.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] In particular, a differential equation is *linear* if it is linear in terms of the unknown function and its derivatives, even if nonlinear in terms of the other variables appearing in it.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] As nonlinear dynamical equations are difficult to solve, nonlinear systems are commonly approximated by linear equations (linearization).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This works well up to some accuracy and some range for the input values, but some interesting phenomena such as solitons, chaos, and singularities are hidden by linearization.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] It follows that some aspects of the dynamic behavior of a nonlinear system can appear to be counterintuitive, unpredictable or even chaotic.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Although such chaotic behavior may resemble random behavior, it is in fact not random.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] For example, some aspects of the weather are seen to be chaotic, where simple changes in one part of the system produce complex effects throughout.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This nonlinearity is one of the reasons why accurate long-term forecasts are impossible with current technology.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Some authors use the term **nonlinear science** for the study of nonlinear systems.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Additivity implies homogeneity for any rational *α*, and, for continuous functions, for any real *α*.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] For a complex *α*, homogeneity does not follow from additivity.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] For example, an antilinear map is additive but not homogeneous.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] is called **linear** if $f(x)$ is a linear map (as defined above) and **nonlinear** otherwise.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] The equation is called *homogeneous* if $C=0$ and $f(x)$ is a homogeneous function.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] The definition $f(x)=C$ is very general in that x can be any sensible mathematical object (number, vector, function, etc.), and the function $f(x)$ can literally be any mapping, including integration or differentiation with associated constraints (such as boundary values).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] If $f(x)$ contains differentiation with respect to x , the result will be a differential equation.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear system of equations consists of a set of equations in several variables such that at least one of them is not a linear equation.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] For a single equation of the form $f(x)=0,$ many methods have been designed; see Root-finding algorithm.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] In the case where f is a polynomial, one has a *polynomial equation* such as $x^{2}+x-1=0.$ The general root-finding algorithms apply to polynomial roots, but, generally they do not find all the roots, and when they fail to find a root, this does not imply that there is no roots.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Specific methods for polynomials allow finding all roots or the real roots; see real-root isolation.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Solving systems of polynomial equations, that is finding the common zeros of a set of several polynomials in several variables is a difficult problem for which elaborate algorithms have been designed, such as Gröbner base algorithms.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] For the general case of system of equations formed by equating to zero several differentiable functions, the main method is Newton's method and its variants.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Generally they may provide a solution, but do not provide any information on the number of solutions.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear recurrence relation defines successive terms of a sequence as a nonlinear function of preceding terms.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear recurrence relations are the logistic map and the relations that define the various Hofstadter sequences.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear discrete models that represent a wide class of nonlinear recurrence relationships include the NARMAX (Nonlinear Autoregressive Moving Average with eXogenous inputs) model and the related nonlinear system identification and analysis procedures.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] These approaches can be used to study a wide class of complex nonlinear behaviors in the time, frequency, and spatio-temporal domains.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A system of differential equations is said to be nonlinear if it is not a system of linear equations.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Problems involving nonlinear differential equations are extremely diverse, and methods of solution or analysis are problem dependent.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear differential equations are the Navier–Stokes equations in fluid dynamics and the Lotka–Volterra equations in biology.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] One of the greatest difficulties of nonlinear problems is that it is not generally possible to combine known solutions into new solutions.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] In linear problems, for example, a family of linearly independent solutions can be used to construct general solutions through the superposition principle.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A good example of this is one-dimensional heat transport with Dirichlet boundary conditions, the solution of which can be written as a time-dependent linear combination of sinusoids of differing frequencies; this makes solutions very flexible.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] It is often possible to find several very specific solutions to nonlinear equations, however the lack of a superposition principle prevents the construction of new solutions.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] First order ordinary differential equations are often exactly solvable by separation of variables, especially for autonomous equations.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] has $u={\frac {1}{x+C}}$ as a general solution (and also the special solution $u=0,$ corresponding to the limit of the general solution when *C* tends to infinity).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] and the left-hand side of the equation is not a linear function of u and its derivatives.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Note that if the $u^{2}$ term were replaced with u , the problem would be linear (the exponential decay problem).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Second and higher order ordinary differential equations (more generally, systems of nonlinear equations) rarely yield closed-form solutions, though implicit solutions and solutions involving nonelementary integrals are encountered.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] The most common basic approach to studying nonlinear partial differential equations is to change the variables (or otherwise transform the problem) so that the resulting problem is simpler (possibly linear).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Sometimes, the equation may be transformed into one or more ordinary differential equations, as seen in separation of variables, which is always useful whether or not the resulting ordinary differential equation(s) is solvable.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Another common (though less mathematical) tactic, often exploited in fluid and heat mechanics, is to use scale analysis to simplify a general, natural equation in a certain specific boundary value problem.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Other methods include examining the characteristics and using the methods outlined above for ordinary differential equations.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A classic, extensively studied nonlinear problem is the dynamics of a frictionless pendulum under the influence of gravity.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] where gravity points "downwards" and $\theta$ is the angle the pendulum forms with its rest position, as shown in the figure at right.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] which is an implicit solution involving an elliptic integral.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This "solution" generally does not have many uses because most of the nature of the solution is hidden in the nonelementary integral (nonelementary unless $C_{0}=2$ ).
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Another way to approach the problem is to linearize any nonlinearity (the sine function term in this case) at the various points of interest through Taylor expansions.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \theta$ for $\theta \approx 0$ .
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This is a simple harmonic oscillator corresponding to oscillations of the pendulum near the bottom of its path.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \pi -\theta$ for $\theta \approx \pi$ .
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] The solution to this problem involves hyperbolic sinusoids, and note that unlike the small angle approximation, this approximation is unstable, meaning that $|\theta |$ will usually grow without limit, though bounded solutions are possible.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to the difficulty of balancing a pendulum upright, it is literally an unstable state.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to a free fall problem.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] A very useful qualitative picture of the pendulum's dynamics may be obtained by piecing together such linearizations, as seen in the figure at right.
[src:spice-simulation/nonlinear-system] Other techniques may be used to find (exact) phase portraits and approximate periods.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The ultimate goal of process simulation is an accurate prediction of the active dopant distribution, the stress distribution and the device geometry.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation is typically used as an input for device simulation, the modeling of device electrical characteristics.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Collectively process and device simulation form the core tools for the design phase known as technology computer aided design (TCAD).
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Considering the integrated circuit design process as a series of steps with decreasing levels of abstraction, logic synthesis would be at the highest level and TCAD, being closest to fabrication, would be the phase with the least amount of abstraction.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Because of the detailed physical modeling involved, process simulation is almost exclusively used to aid in the development of single devices whether discrete or as a part of an integrated circuit.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The fabrication of integrated circuit devices requires a series of processing steps called a process flow.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation involves modeling all essential steps in the process flow in order to obtain dopant and stress profiles and, to a lesser extent, device geometry.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The input for process simulation is the process flow and a layout.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The layout is selected as a linear cut in a full layout for a 2D simulation or a rectangular cut from the layout for a 3D simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] TCAD has traditionally focused mainly on the transistor fabrication part of the process flow ending with the formation of source and drain contacts—also known as front end of line manufacturing.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Back end of line manufacturing, e.g. interconnect and dielectric layers are not considered.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] One reason for delineation is the availability of powerful analysis tools such as electron microscopy techniques, scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM), which allow for accurate measurement of device geometry.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] There are no similar tools available for accurate high resolution measurement of dopant or stress profiles.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Nevertheless, there is growing interest to investigate the interaction between front end and back end manufacturing steps.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] For example, back end manufacturing may cause stress in the transistor region changing device performance.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] These interactions will stimulate the need for better interfaces to back end simulation tools or lead to integration of some of those capabilities into TCAD tools.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In addition to the recent expanding scope of process simulation, there has always been a desire to have more accurate simulations.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] However, simplified physical models have been most commonly used in order to minimize computation time.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] But, shrinking device dimensions put increasing demands on the accuracy of dopant and stress profiles so new process models are added for each generation of devices to match new accuracy demands.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Many of the models were conceived by researchers long before they were needed, but sometimes new effects are only recognized and understood once process engineers discover a problem and experiments are performed.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In any case, the trend of adding more physical models and considering more detailed physical effects will continue and may accelerate.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The history of commercial process simulators began with the development of the Stanford University Process Engineering Models (SUPREM) program.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] SUPREM was the resulting software from research by Stanford professor Robert Dutton (engineer).
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Building upon this beginning with improved models SUPREM II and SUPREM III were developed.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] (TMA) was co-founded by Robert Dutton (engineer) in 1979.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] TMA was the first company to commercialize SUPREM III.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Later Silvaco also commercialized SUPREM and named the product ATHENA.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] TMA commercialized SUPREM-IV (2D version) and called it TSUPREM4.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 1992, Integrated Systems Engineering (ISE) came out with the 1D process simulator TESIM and the 2D process simulator DIOS.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] At about the same time development of a new 3D process and device simulator began at TMA and after TMA was acquired by Avanti, the product was released in 1998 as Taurus.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Around 1994 a first version of the Florida Object Oriented Process Simulator (FLOOPS) was completed.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] FLOOPS was later commercialized by ISE in 2002.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] One other process simulator PROPHET was created around 1994 at Bell labs which later became Agere, but has not been sold commercially.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 2002 Synopsys acquired Avant!, corp. and in 2004 Synopsys acquired ISE.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Synopsys combined the features of Taurus and TSUPREM4, into the FLOOPS platform and called it Sentaurus Process.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Current Silvaco products are Victory Process and Victory Device for 2D/3D simulation, and legacy products Athena for 2D process simulation, and Atlas for 2D device simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In 2013, Coventor released SEMulator3D, an advanced process simulator based upon voxel modeling and surface evolution.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Besides these simulators, there are numerous other university and commercial simulators such as PROMIS, PREDICT, PROSIM, ICECREM, DADOS, TITAN, MicroTec, DOPDEES, ALAMODE.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The process steps most often associated with process simulation are ion implantation, annealing (diffusion and dopant activation), etch, deposition, oxidation, and epitaxy.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Other common steps include chemical-mechanical planarization (CMP), silicidation, and reflow.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] All commercial process simulators use a combination of the finite element analysis (FE) and/or finite volume methods (FV) methods.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] A complete description of FE/FV method is out of the scope of this article but there are many fine books which describe the topic thoroughly.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] However, it is important to discuss requirements for process simulation for achieving accurate results.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] These requirements are based on the same requirements as generic to FE/FV techniques with an additional difficulty coming from the changes in the geometry during the simulated fabrication of the device.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation uses an FE/FV mesh to compute and store the dopant and stress profiles.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Each geometrical change in the simulation domain requires a new mesh which fits to the new boundaries.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] As will be described below, the large number of geometry modifying steps involved and the nature of process simulation where each step depends on the cumulative results of all previous steps, make process simulation an especially challenging application of the FE/FV technique.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] One of the most important results of process simulation is the dopant profile after processing.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The accuracy of the profile strongly depends on maintaining a proper density of mesh points at any time during the simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The density of points should be just enough to resolve all dopant and defect profiles but not more because the computation expense of solving the diffusion equations increases with the number of mesh points.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] A typical full flow CMOS process simulation can have more than 50 mesh changes and the number of mesh changes can increase dramatically if adaptive meshing is performed.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] For each mesh change, interpolation is used to obtain data values on the new mesh.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] It is important to manage the mesh changes in such a way to avoid accuracy degradation due to interpolation error.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] The easiest way to do this is to always keep points once they are introduced into the mesh, but this has the drawback of producing very many mesh points which can be computationally expensive.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Maintaining a balance between interpolation error, computational expense, and minimization of required user input is important for obtaining accurate results with a minimum of computational expense.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] This is especially true when simulating devices in 3D.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Without careful placement of mesh either the accuracy will suffer unacceptably, or the computational expense will be too great to be useful.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Process simulation tools so far have had limited success in completely automating mesh adaptation such that no user intervention is required.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] This places a requirement of the user to understand meshing and how it affects simulation accuracy and run time and the burdens the user to track mesh changes during the simulation to ensure proper mesh is maintained.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] One of the most important uses of TCAD tools is to explore new device technology where many exploratory simulations are performed in order to give the device designer a better understanding of possible benefits as well as drawbacks of a specific technology.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] This use case demands sequential simulations with some analysis in between.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] In order to be useful, many simulation cycles must be run within the time allotted for exploration, putting a high priority on minimization of simulation run time.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Currently, full flow standard CMOS simulations are most often accomplished with a combination of 1D and 2D simulation and take less than a few hours on a 2.6 GHz Pentium 4.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] To perform these simulations in 3D (from gate formation on) would take a minimum of 24 hours for minimum accuracy simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] Most of the information desired from TCAD simulations can be extracted from the simplification that the device can be treated uniformly in depth (i.e. a 2D simulation).
[src:spice-simulation/semiconductor-process-simulation] To include the effects device shape along the depth or to investigate implant shadowing, 3D simulations must be performed.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Unlike board-level designs composed of discrete parts, it is not practical to breadboard integrated circuits before manufacture.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Further, the high costs of photolithographic masks and other manufacturing prerequisites make it essential to design the circuit to be as close to perfect as possible before the integrated circuit is first built.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Simulating the circuit with SPICE is the industry-standard way to verify circuit operation at the transistor level before committing to manufacturing an integrated circuit.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The SPICE simulators help to predict the behavior of the IC under different operating conditions, such as different voltage and current levels, temperature variations, and noise.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Board-level circuit designs can often be breadboarded for testing.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Even with a breadboard, some circuit properties may not be accurate compared to the final printed wiring board, such as parasitic resistances and capacitances, whose effects can often be estimated more accurately using simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Also, designers may want more information about the circuit than is available from a single mock-up.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] For instance, circuit performance is affected by component manufacturing tolerances.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In these cases, it is common to use SPICE to perform Monte Carlo simulations of the effect of component variations on performance, a task which is impractical using calculations by hand for a circuit of any appreciable complexity.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Circuit simulation programs, of which SPICE and derivatives are the most prominent, take a text netlist describing the circuit elements (transistors, resistors, capacitors, etc.) and their connections, and translate this description into equations to be solved.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The general equations produced are nonlinear differential algebraic equations, which are solved using implicit integration methods, Newton's method and sparse matrix techniques.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE was developed at the Electronics Research Laboratory of the University of California, Berkeley by Laurence W.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Nagel with direction from his research advisor, Prof.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE1 is largely a derivative of the CANCER program, which Nagel had worked on under Prof.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] CANCER is an acronym for "Computer Analysis of Nonlinear Circuits, Excluding Radiation".
[src:spice-simulation/spice] At these times many circuit simulators were developed under contracts with the United States Department of Defense that needed the ability to evaluate the radiation hardness of a circuit.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Pederson insisted that CANCER, a proprietary program, be rewritten enough that restrictions could be removed and the program could be put in the public domain.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE1 was first presented at a conference in 1973.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE1 is coded in FORTRAN and to construct the circuit equations uses nodal analysis, which has limitations in representing inductors, floating voltage sources and the various forms of controlled sources.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE1 has relatively few circuit elements available and uses a fixed-timestep transient analysis.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The real popularity of SPICE started with SPICE2 in 1975.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Ellis Cohen led development from version 2B to the industry standard SPICE 2G6, the last FORTRAN version, released in 1983.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE3 was developed by Thomas Quarles (with A.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] It is written in C, uses the same netlist syntax, and adds X Window System plotting.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] As an early public domain software program with source code available, SPICE was widely distributed and used.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Its ubiquity became such that "to SPICE a circuit" remains synonymous with circuit simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE source code was from the beginning distributed by UC Berkeley for a nominal charge (to cover the cost of magnetic tape).
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The license originally included distribution restrictions for countries not considered friendly to the US, but the source code is currently covered by the BSD license.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The birth of SPICE was named an IEEE Milestone in 2011; the entry mentions that SPICE "evolved to become the worldwide standard integrated circuit simulator".
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Nagel was awarded the 2019 IEEE Donald O.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Pederson Award in Solid-State Circuits for the development of SPICE.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] No newer versions of Berkeley SPICE have been released after version 3f5 in 1993.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Berkeley SPICE inspired and served as a basis for many other circuit simulation programs, in academia, in industry, and in commercial products.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The first commercial version of SPICE is ISPICE, an interactive version on a timeshare service, National CSS.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The most prominent commercial versions of SPICE include HSPICE (originally commercialized by Ashawna and Kim Hailey of Meta Software, but now owned by Synopsys) and PSPICE (now owned by Cadence Design Systems).
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The integrated circuit industry adopted SPICE quickly, and until commercial versions became well developed, many IC design houses had proprietary versions of SPICE.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Today a few IC manufacturers, typically the larger companies, have groups continuing to develop SPICE-based circuit simulation programs.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Both LTspice and TINA-TI come bundled with models from their respective companies.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Other companies maintain internal circuit simulators which are not directly based upon SPICE, among them PowerSpice at IBM, TITAN at Infineon Technologies, Lynx at Intel Corporation, and Pstar at NXP Semiconductors also.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE became popular because it contained the analyses and models needed to design integrated circuits of the time, and was robust enough and fast enough to be practical to use.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Precursors to SPICE often had a single purpose: The BIAS program, for example, did simulation of bipolar transistor circuit operating points; the SLIC program did only small-signal analyses.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE combined operating point solutions, transient analysis, and various small-signal analyses with the circuit elements and device models needed to successfully simulate many circuits.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Since SPICE is generally used to model circuits with nonlinear elements, the small signal analyses are necessarily preceded by a quiescent point calculation at which the circuit is linearized.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE2 also contains code for other small-signal analyses: sensitivity analysis, pole-zero analysis, and small-signal distortion analysis.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Analysis at various temperatures is done by automatically updating semiconductor model parameters for temperature, allowing the circuit to be simulated at temperature extremes.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Other circuit simulators have since added many analyses beyond those in SPICE2 to address changing industry requirements.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Parametric sweeps were added to analyze circuit performance with changing manufacturing tolerances or operating conditions.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Loop gain and stability calculations were added for analog circuits.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Harmonic balance or time-domain steady state analyses were added for RF and switched-capacitor circuit design.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] However, a public-domain circuit simulator containing the modern analyses and features needed to become a successor in popularity to SPICE has not yet emerged.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] It is very important to use appropriate analyses with carefully chosen parameters.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] For example, the application of linear analysis to nonlinear circuits should be justified separately.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Also, application of transient analysis with default simulation parameters can lead to qualitatively wrong conclusions on circuit dynamics.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE2 includes many semiconductor device compact models: three levels of MOSFET model, a combined Ebers–Moll and Gummel–Poon bipolar model, a JFET model, and a model for a junction diode.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In addition, it had many other elements: resistors, capacitors, inductors (including coupling), independent voltage and current sources, ideal transmission lines, active components and voltage and current controlled sources.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE3 added more sophisticated MOSFET models, which were needed due to advances in semiconductor technology.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In particular, the BSIM family of models was added, which was also developed at UC Berkeley.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Commercial and industrial SPICE simulators have added many other device models as technology advanced and earlier models became inadequate.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] To attempt standardization of these models so that a set of model parameters may be used in different simulators, an industry working group was formed, the Compact Model Council, to choose, maintain and promote the use of standard models.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] The standard models today include BSIM3, BSIM4, BSIMSOI, PSP, HICUM, and MEXTRAM.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Spice can use device models from foundry PDKs.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE2 takes a text netlist as input and produces line-printer listings as output, which fit with the computing environment in 1975.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] These listings are either columns of numbers corresponding to calculated outputs (typically voltages or currents), or line-printer character "plots".
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE3 retains the netlist for circuit description, but allows analyses to be controlled from a command-line interface similar to the C shell.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE3 also added basic X plotting, as UNIX and engineering workstations became common.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Vendors and various free software projects have added schematic capture frontends to SPICE, allowing a schematic diagram of the circuit to be drawn and the netlist to be automatically generated and transferred to various SPICE backends.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Also, graphical user interfaces were added for selecting the simulations to be done and manipulating the voltage and current output vectors.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In addition, very capable graphing utilities have been added to see waveforms and graphs of parametric dependencies.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Several free versions of these extended programs are available.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] As SPICE generally solves non-linear differential algebraic equations, it may be applied to simulating beyond the electrical realm.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In the simplest case, SPICE can be used to simulate other flows.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] For example, heat flow in systems follows similar behavior to ideal electrical circuit elements: temperature corresponds to voltage, heat capacity corresponds to capacitance, (thermal) conductance to (electrical) conductance, and heat flow to current.).
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE can thus simulate both the electronic behavior of a circuit and its heat dissipation requirements simultaneously.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Likewise micro-fluidic circuits have been modelled with SPICE through the hydrodynamic analogy.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE has been applied in **operations research** to evaluate perturbed supply chains, and regulatory networks in synthetic biology.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] However, transport dynamics are not a requirement for SPICE simulation.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] In a rotating machine, torque corresponds to voltage, angular velocity to current, viscous friction to resistance, and inertia to inductance.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] SPICE has been used to model loudspeakers, earphones, and headphones.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Such electro-mechanical transducers often have complex input impedances (see, for example, Electrical characteristics of dynamic loudspeakers) that present difficulties to the circuits designed to drive them.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Integrated modelling of both components addresses this problem.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Electromagnetic modeling is accessible to a SPICE simulator via the PEEC (partial element equivalent circuit) method.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] Maxwell's equations have been mapped, RLC, Skin effect, dielectric or magnetic materials and incident or radiated fields have been modelled.
[src:spice-simulation/spice] However, as of 2019, SPICE cannot simulate arbitrary photonic dynamics when circuits display strongly quantum effects.
